===Standard Helical Gears===

As above with no profile shifting but the helix angle (<math> \beta</math>) is taken into account.

{| class="wikitable"
|+ style="text-align: left;" | Helical and double helical gearing
|-
! Symbol !! Term !! Formula
|-
| <math>m_t</math>
| ''Transverse Module''
| <math>m_t = \frac {m_n} {\cos (\beta)}</math>
|-
| <math>m_n</math>
| ''Normal Module''
| <math>m_n = m_t \cdot {\cos (\beta)}</math>
|-
| <math>p_t</math>
| ''Transverse Pitch''
| <math>p_t = \pi \cdot m_t = \pi \cdot \frac {m_n} {\cos (\beta)}</math>
|-
| <math>p_n</math>
| ''Normal Pitch''
| <math>p_n = \pi \cdot m_n = \pi \cdot m_t \cdot \cos (\beta)</math>
|-
| <math>d</math>
| ''Pitch Diameter''
| <math>d = z \cdot m_t = z \cdot \frac {m_n} {\cos (\beta)}</math>
|}
* Addendum and dedendum are  also controlled by the normal module.
* It depends on the {{PropertyData|properties_from_tool}} property if the {{PropertyData|module}} property is used as normal module or transverse module.

==Scripting==

Use the power of Python to automate your gear modeling:

{{Code|code=
import FreeCAD as App
import FreeCADGui as Gui
import freecad.gears.commands
gear = freecad.gears.commands.CreateInvoluteGear.create()
gear.num_teeth = 20
gear.helix_angle = 20
gear.height = 10
gear.double_helix = True
App.ActiveDocument.recompute()
Gui.SendMsgToActiveView("ViewFit")
}}


